  "html_columbia": null,
  "html_with_citations": "\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">United States Court of Appeals</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">For the First Circuit</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">No. 00-2392</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">HOME OWNERS SAVINGS BANK, F.S.B.,</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Plaintiffs, Appellees,</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">v.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">KEY FINANCIAL SERVICES, INC.,</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Defendant, Appellant.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">APPEAL FROM THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">FOR THE DISTRICT OF MASSACHUSETTS</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">[Hon. Douglas P. Woodlock, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">U.S. District Judge</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">]</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Before</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> Selya, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Circuit Judge</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">,</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Stahl, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Senior Circuit Judge</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, </span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">and Lynch, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Circuit Judge</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Daniel R. Warren</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, with whom </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Melissa M. Eckhause</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, and </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; Flory LLP</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, were on brief, for appellant.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">J. Scott Watson</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, Attorney, with whom </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Ann S. DuRoss</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, Assistant General Counsel, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Colleen J. Boles</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, Senior Counsel, and </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Jaclyn C. Taner</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, Counsel, were on brief, for appellees.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<table border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\">\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\">\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">February 12, 2002</span>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\">\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n</td>\n</tr></tbody></table><p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">STAHL, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Senior Circuit Judge</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';).</span>\n</p><p>1:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; will be used to refer collectively to the original plaintiff and its successors in interest. </span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s arguments without merit, we affirm the rulings below.</span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">I.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; 2.5 or other related sections would require Key to repurchase, upon demand, the non-conforming mortgages.</span>\n</p><p>2:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';  Despite this guarantee, Home Owners identified over 100 loans with non-conforming policies.  All of the mortgages in question were originated</span>\n</p><p>3:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; refers to the lender who initially dealt with the customer.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; meaning that the consumer had a marginal credit history.</span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; demand that the disputed mortgages be repurchased, Home Owners in 1989 filed suit in federal court.</span>\n</p><p>4:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; this demand by letter dated August 31, 1989, Key filed suit.  Key, on the other hand, insists that Home Owners did not formally demand that Key repurchase the disputed mortgages until April 6, 1990.  As the district court began its calculation of damages from the April 1990 date, any dispute over this point amounts to nothing of importance.  </span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">  Count I of its complaint alleged breach of contract, asserting that Key had materially breached its representation in </span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; 3.1 of the Agreement, which required Key to repurchase all non-conforming loans.  Key filed a cross-motion for summary judgment, alleging, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">inter alia</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; 2.5(o).</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Applying New York law,</span>\n</p><p>5:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; and (4) were not on ALTA forms and contained exceptions</span>\n<p>6:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';s liens and excluded any matter arising or occurring before the date the borrower acquired title.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';  </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Home Owners Savings Bank</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> v. </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Key Fin. Servs., Inc.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';).</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">  Having found Key liable,</span>\n<p>7:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; second motion for partial summary judgment dismissing the affirmative defenses, a ruling which Key has not appealed.  Accordingly, we focus solely on the breach of contract claim. </span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> the court gave the parties one week to submit a proposed final judgment to bring the matter to a close.  </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Id.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> at 16.</span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; portfolio either because of foreclosure or because the interest in the loan had been sold.  The parties disagreed as to how the off-line loans should be taken into account when crafting a final judgment.  Unable to reach a mutually acceptable rationale, Home Owners filed a proposed judgment in May 1992, which Key opposed.  Home Owners then filed a motion for summary judgment on the issue of damages.  </span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; 3.1, was an independent breach of the Agreement.  Accordingly, it found that Home Owners was entitled to pursue general contract remedies for breach of contract.  The calculation of damages, however, was left for further proceedings after both parties conducted discovery.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Over the next three years, the district court was faced with numerous discovery disputes and motions in limine regarding the issue of damages.  Finally, in 1999, the district court issued an order awarding Home Owners damages and prejudgment interest dating back to April 1990.  </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">See</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">supra</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> note 4.  Finding that there were no outstanding issues of material fact regarding the computation of principal and interest, the district court on September 29, 2000 entered final judgment for Home Owners in the amount $8,509,609.64.</span>\n</p><p>8:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">  The judgment also awarded litigation costs, post-judgment interest and photocopying expenses to Home Owners.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">  Key timely appealed.</span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">II.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; 2.5(o) of the Agreement.  Instead, Key asserts that whatever breach it committed was not material, and therefore it had no obligation to repurchase the loans at issue.  Specifically, Key argues that the district court applied the wrong standard of materiality when it decided as a matter of law to grant partial summary judgment in favor of Home Owners with regard to the breach of contract claim.  Furthermore, Key insists that the issue of materiality is highly fact dependent, thereby precluding resolution of the issue by motion for summary judgment. </span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; 2.5(o) of the Agreement in the various ways detailed </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">supra</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s breaches were material, the district court cited the standard articulated in </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">United States ex rel. Roman</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> v. </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Schlesinger</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';  </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Times Mirror Magazines, Inc.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> v. </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; Stream Licenses Co.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">, <span class=\"citation\" data-id=\"2469712\"><a href=\"/opinion/2469712/times-mirror-magazines-inc-v-field-stream-licenses-co/\"><span class=\"volume\">103</span> <span class=\"reporter\">F. Supp. 2d</span> <span class=\"page\">711</span></a></span>, 731 (S.D.N.Y. 2000) (internal quotations omitted).  </span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';</span>\n</p><p>9:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; </span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s characterization of this case as one involving rescission without any further explanation, </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">see</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s reliance on the materiality standard from </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Schlesinger</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s citation of the </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Times Mirror</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"> materiality test, which was crafted in the context of a case where the nonbreaching party sought rescission from the court rather than seeking relief based on a contractual provision, is inapposite as well.</span>\n</p><p>10:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">  Rather than turning to pure rescission cases or fraudulent inducement cases for guidance, we find this case to be particularly analogous to a case involving the breach of an express warranty.  Key warranted that the loans would be Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac compliant, and that the title policies would be on ALTA forms, thereby incorporating the standard protections included thereon.  These explicit warranties were breached.  Because there can be no dispute about the existence of these express warranties, it appears that, under New York law, Home Owners need not even prove that it had actually relied on the warranties when entering into the transaction.  </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">See</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\"> </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';l Inc.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\"> v. </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">McKesson Corp.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">see also</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">SCBS Inc.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\"> v. </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';g</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">, <span class=\"citation no-link\"><span class=\"volume\">553</span> <span class=\"reporter\">N.E.2d</span> <span class=\"page\">997</span></span>, 1001 (N.Y. 1990) (affirming the </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';\">CPC</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';). </span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';</span>\n<p>11:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; 2.5.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s rulings regarding liability.</span>\n<p>12:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; alleged intentions at the time it entered into the transaction.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">III.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; sole remedy under the contract, and therefore, awarding general contract damages provides Home Owners with a windfall.</span>\n</p><p>13:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman';</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s argument is misplaced.  Whether or not Key committed an independent breach by failing to repurchase on demand, the district court was free to make Home Owners whole, and it did so in terms of the obligation imposed by the contract. </span>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s failure to do so.  A repurchase provision is designed to shift the risk to the selling party in the event that a dispute arises.</span>\n</p><p>14:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; title policies.  Section 3.1 obligated Key to repurchase these faulty  mortgages upon demand, meaning that from the moment a proper repurchase demand was made, Key -- not Home Owners -- should have borne the risk of any market fluctuations.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier'; will result from the fact that the vast majority of the disputed loans have gone off-line.</span>\n<p>15:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; for Home Owners.</span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s cries of injustice fall on deaf ears, as Key freely contracted for the obligations by which it now finds itself bound.</span>\n<p>16:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.5000inch;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Times New Roman'; relief for the non-breaching party in light of the fact that the prenegotiated remedy provision had failed in its purpose because many of the loans had gone off-line. </span>\n</p>\n<p/>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';s assessment.  Had Key satisfied its repurchase obligation immediately, many of these arguments over documentation would never have materialized.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">IV.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:1.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">After almost a decade of litigation, which helped to make the record below not always a model of clarity, we are satisfied that the various rulings and final judgment ultimately entered by the district court were sound. </span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Affirmed.</span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">  </span>\n<span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\">Costs to Appellees.</span>\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-indent:0.0000inch;line-height:2.000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: 'Courier';\"/>\n</p>\n\n",
